{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Pin the release supply chain to immutable references\n\nMake every executable the release depends on identifiable by an immutable\nreference: full-SHA action pins, a hash-locked build environment, an\nexact-versioned + digest-verified MCP publisher, and non-persisted checkout\ncredentials. (Readiness Finding 4 ŌĆö verified VALID against `release.yml`\nlines 31/32/43/60/65/85/124/129 and `pyproject.toml:1-3`.)\n\n## Why\n\nTwo release runs of the same rebar SHA can execute different build/upload/publish\ncode today. `release.yml` references first-party actions by moving major-version\ntags (`actions/checkout@v7` at :31/:124, `actions/setup-python@v6` at :32,\n`actions/upload-artifact@v7` at :43, `actions/download-artifact@v8` at :60/:85);\ninstalls build tools with unrestricted upgrades (`pip install --upgrade build`\n:37, `--upgrade twine` :41); publishes via the branch-like `pypa/gh-action-pypi-publish@release/v1`\n(:65); declares the build backend as bare `hatchling` (`pyproject.toml:1-3`); and\nin the `mcp_registry` job downloads its publisher from a mutable `releases/latest`\nURL and executes it **without a digest/signature check** (:129) in a job that holds\n`id-token: write` (used for GitHub OIDC login + registry publication). None of the\ncheckouts set `persist-credentials: false`, so the token persists in local git\nconfig by default. The repo SHA-pins **some** third-party actions in\n`gerrit-verify.yaml` (its header claims comprehensive pinning, but e.g.\n`gerrit-verify.yaml:75` still has an unpinned `actions/setup-python@v6`), so the\ngeneric action-security checks are not yet enforced on `release.yml`. Rather than\nhand-roll regex checks, this story adopts the **proven, maintained tools** ŌĆö\n`zizmor` (GitHub-Actions security auditor: unpinned actions, credential persistence,\nover-broad/dangerous permissions incl. OIDC) and `actionlint` ŌĆö run under\n`make lint`, plus a thin project-specific test for the rebar-only invariants zizmor\ndoesn't know about. (Fixing `gerrit-verify.yaml`'s own unpinned `setup-python` is\nout of scope ŌĆö this story touches only `release.yml` and the shared lint config.)\n\n## What\n\nAdopt the uv / pip pinning pattern (uv: full-SHA action pins, `persist-credentials:\nfalse`, a pinned release tool with a verified SHA-256; pip: SHA-pinned actions +\na hash-locked build environment installed with `--require-hashes --no-deps`):\n\n- Replace each action tag with a full commit SHA, keeping the human-readable\n  version in a trailing comment.\n- Set `persist-credentials: false` on every release checkout unless a later git\n  operation demonstrably needs the persisted credential.\n- **Enforce the generic action-security checks with `zizmor` + `actionlint` (proven\n  tools, not hand-rolled).** Add `zizmor` (itself version+hash-pinned in the release\n  lock) and `actionlint` to `make lint` so they run under the Gerrit `Verified` gate.\n  `zizmor` enforces full-SHA pinning of `uses:`, `persist-credentials: false`, and\n  over-broad/dangerous permissions (including OIDC) across `release.yml`. A thin\n  `tests/unit/test_release_workflow_pins.py` (also under `make test`) then asserts\n  only the **rebar-specific** invariants `zizmor` cannot know: the `--no-isolation`\n  build flag, the `mcp_verify`(no `id-token`)/`mcp_registry`(has it) split, the\n  `chmod +x mcp-publisher` step, the evidence-fragment wiring, and the\n  `docs/releasing.md` \"Pinning\" section substrings.\n- Create a reviewed release lock/constraints file covering `build`, Hatchling,\n  Twine, any artifact-validation tools, and their transitive deps, generated and\n  maintained with an established tool ŌĆö **`pip-compile --generate-hashes` (pip-tools)**\n  (or `uv pip compile --generate-hashes`) ŌĆö checked into the repo.\n- **Hatchling enforcement ŌĆö decision.** pip's default `python -m build` resolves the\n  `[build-system]` requires in a *fresh isolated env*, so the lock only governs\n  Hatchling's version if the build uses the pre-installed locked env. **This story\n  uses `--no-isolation`**: pre-install the hash-locked env (including Hatchling)\n  with `pip install --require-hashes -r .github/release-requirements.txt`, then `python -m build\n  --no-isolation`. This keeps enforcement entirely in the workflow and avoids\n  editing `pyproject.toml` `[build-system]`. **Close the ambient-package hole:**\n  because `ubuntu-latest` ships `pip`/`setuptools`/`wheel`/`packaging` and the\n  `--no-isolation` build runs in the ambient env, after the hash-locked install\n  **diff `pip freeze` against `.github/release-requirements.txt` and fail on any extra\n  or version-mismatched package** ŌĆö so a build-time import can't silently resolve to\n  an unpinned ambient package. The `test_release_workflow_pins.py` test (run by `make test`) fails if\n  `--no-isolation` is absent (so no free-resolution path can silently return).\n- **MCP publisher ŌĆö download ŌåÆ verify ŌåÆ execute (never stream into tar).** Replace\n  the `releases/latest` URL with an exact version, and split the current\n  `curl ŌĆ” | tar xz` one-liner into three ordered steps so an unverified archive is\n  never extracted or executed:\n  1. `curl -fsSL \"<exact-version-url>\" -o mcp-publisher.tar.gz`\n  2. `echo \"<pinned-sha256>  mcp-publisher.tar.gz\" | sha256sum -c --strict`\n  3. `tar xzf mcp-publisher.tar.gz mcp-publisher`\n  Prefer an upstream `checksums.txt` if `modelcontextprotocol/registry` ships one;\n  otherwise hard-code the SHA-256 computed at pin time with a rationale comment.\n  **Arch note:** the current download URL is built from `uname -s`/`uname -m`, so the\n  `<url, sha256>` pair is arch-specific. `release.yml` runs on `ubuntu-latest`\n  (linux/amd64), so pin the `linux_amd64` URL + its SHA-256 as a single deliberate\n  pair (documented, with a revisit note if the runner arch changes); store one pair\n  per supported OS/arch tuple if the matrix ever expands.\n  **Security contract ŌĆö structural job split (not step ordering).** This follows\n  GitHub's own *Security hardening for GitHub Actions* guidance (least-privilege\n  permissions; isolate privileged operations into their own job) and the PyPA\n  Trusted-Publishing model of minimizing what runs under the OIDC token. In GitHub\n  Actions `id-token: write` is a *job-level* permission: the OIDC token endpoint\n  (`$ACTIONS_ID_TOKEN_REQUEST_URL`) is reachable from the job's **first** step, so\n  step ordering within one job does NOT prevent a compromised archive from minting a\n  token during the download step. Enforce co-residency structurally by **splitting\n  the job in two**: `mcp_verify` (no `id-token: write`; runs curl download +\n  `sha256sum -c` and uploads the verified binary as an artifact / sets a `verified`\n  output) and `mcp_registry` (`needs: mcp_verify`; holds `id-token: write`; consumes\n  the already-verified artifact and runs `mcp-publisher login`/`publish`). Fail on an\n  unexpected filename/size/digest/version. So the OIDC-privileged job never downloads\n  or holds an unverified binary. **Restore the executable bit after the handoff:**\n  `actions/upload-artifact` (v3+) does not preserve POSIX permissions, so\n  `mcp_registry` must `chmod +x mcp-publisher` after `download-artifact` or the\n  `./mcp-publisher login` call fails \"Permission denied\" at runtime.\n- Print and retain release evidence. GitHub Actions artifacts are **job-scoped** and\n  cannot be appended to across jobs, so each job uploads its **own distinctly-named**\n  fragment (`evidence-shapin`, `evidence-build`, `evidence-mcp`; Finding 3 later adds\n  `evidence-artifacts` for the wheel/sdist sums), and a final aggregation step downloads all fragments and concatenates them into one\n  `release-evidence.txt` ŌĆö recording every action SHA, the Python build-tool versions,\n  the MCP publisher version + verified digest, and the wheel/sdist digests.\n- Update pins through reviewed dependency-update changes, not implicit resolution\n  during a production release.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` ŌĆö SHA-pin all `uses:`; `persist-credentials:\n  false`; `--no-isolation` hash-locked build install; split the MCP publisher\n  into an unprivileged `mcp_verify` job + an OIDC-privileged `mcp_registry` job that\n  consumes the verified artifact (coordinate with Findings 1 and 3, which also edit\n  this file).\n- `.github/release-requirements.txt` (new, the hash-locked constraints file) compiled\n  from `.github/release-requirements.in` via\n  `pip-compile --generate-hashes --output-file=.github/release-requirements.txt .github/release-requirements.in`.\n- `Makefile` + shared lint config ŌĆö add `zizmor` (version+hash-pinned in the release\n  lock) and `actionlint` to `make lint` (run by the Gerrit `Verified` gate via\n  `gerrit-verify.yaml`). `zizmor` enforces the **generic** checks on `release.yml`:\n  full-SHA pinning of every `uses:`, `persist-credentials: false`, and\n  over-broad/dangerous permissions (incl. OIDC). A standalone PR-triggered GitHub\n  workflow would NOT run pre-merge in this repo's Gerrit flow, which is why the lint\n  runs under `make lint`, not a `pull_request` trigger.\n- `tests/unit/test_release_workflow_pins.py` (new) ŌĆö a thin test under `make test`\n  for only the **rebar-specific** invariants `zizmor` can't know, parsing\n  `release.yml` + `docs/releasing.md`: (c) the build invocation includes\n  `--no-isolation`; (d) the `docs/releasing.md` \"Pinning\" section contains the three\n  required substrings (see the docs AC); (e) the job-permission split ŌĆö\n  `mcp_verify` declares no `id-token: write`, `mcp_registry` does (fail if\n  `mcp_verify` gains it); (f) the release-evidence wiring ŌĆö the three fragment names\n  this story delivers (`evidence-shapin|evidence-build|evidence-mcp`) appear in\n  `release.yml` and a consolidation job downloads + concatenates them\n  (`evidence-artifacts` is asserted by Finding 3's story after it lands); (g) a\n  `chmod +x mcp-publisher` step is present in the `mcp_registry` job; (h) an\n  ambient-package guard step (`pip freeze` diffed against the lock) is present.\n- `tests/unit/test_mcp_publisher_pin.py` (new) ŌĆö run by `make test`; writes a test\n  copy of the pinned archive, corrupts one byte, runs the `mcp_verify` `sha256sum -c`\n  logic, and asserts a non-zero exit.\n- `pyproject.toml` ŌĆö **no change** to `[build-system]` requires: with the chosen\n  `--no-isolation` strategy the Hatchling version is governed by the\n  pre-installed hash-locked env, not by `pyproject.toml` (this is deliberate; if the\n  isolated-build path were kept instead, a `[build-system]` pin would be required ŌĆö\n  but it is not kept).\n- `docs/releasing.md` ŌĆö document the pinning policy and the pin-update process.\n  **Section ownership:** this story owns the \"Pinning\" section only (Finding 1 owns\n  \"Release-source authorization\", Finding 3 owns \"Build-once\"), avoiding overlap\n  across the three concurrent release stories.\n- Out of scope: pinning non-release workflows already SHA-pinned; full reproducible\n  builds (covered adjacent to Finding 3).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every `uses:` in `release.yml` references a full 40-char commit SHA with a\n  trailing version comment ŌĆö enforced by `zizmor` (via `make lint`), which fails on\n  any unpinned `uses:`.\n- [ ] Every release checkout sets `persist-credentials: false` ŌĆö enforced by `zizmor`\n  (via `make lint`), which flags credential persistence.\n- [ ] `zizmor` + `actionlint` run under `make lint` (so they execute in the Gerrit\n  `Verified` gate), `zizmor` is itself version+hash-pinned in the release lock, and\n  `zizmor` reports no findings on `release.yml` (SHA-pins, persist-credentials,\n  over-broad/OIDC permissions all clean).\n- [ ] Release build tools (`build`, Hatchling, Twine, validation tools) install from\n  `.github/release-requirements.txt` (generated by `pip-compile --generate-hashes\n  --output-file=.github/release-requirements.txt .github/release-requirements.in`)\n  with `--require-hashes` ŌĆö the install itself is the verification: `pip install\n  --require-hashes --no-deps -r .github/release-requirements.txt` re-hashes every artifact against the lock and\n  **fails the build** if any package was replaced or its hash doesn't match (a\n  `--dry-run` would not, since pip skips digest-checking for already-satisfied\n  packages). The install step emits `pip list --format=freeze > tool-versions.txt`\n  into the release evidence artifact.\n- [ ] After the hash-locked install, a guard step diffs `pip freeze` against\n  `.github/release-requirements.txt` and fails on any extra or version-mismatched\n  package (closing the ambient-runner-package hole under `--no-isolation --no-deps`);\n  `test_release_workflow_pins.py` check (h) asserts this guard step is present.\n- [ ] Hatchling's version is enforced end-to-end via `--no-isolation` against\n  the pre-installed hash-locked env (not via a `pyproject.toml` pin), with\n  `test_release_workflow_pins.py` failing if `--no-isolation` is removed from the build\n  invocation (no free-resolution path remains).\n- [ ] The MCP publisher is pinned to an exact version and its archive digest is\n  verified in a separate `mcp_verify` job that has **no** `id-token: write`; the\n  OIDC-privileged `mcp_registry` job `needs: mcp_verify` and consumes only the\n  verified artifact ŌĆö so the OIDC scope is never co-resident with an unverified\n  binary; `mcp_registry` runs `chmod +x mcp-publisher` after `download-artifact`\n  (upload-artifact drops the exec bit). `test_release_workflow_pins.py` additionally\n  asserts the permission structure (`mcp_verify` has no `id-token: write`,\n  `mcp_registry` does) and that the `chmod +x mcp-publisher` step is present. Verified by `test_mcp_publisher_pin.py`, which\n  corrupts one byte of the pinned archive, runs the verify step, and asserts it exits\n  non-zero. If upstream ships no checksums, the pinned SHA-256 is hard-coded in\n  the workflow with a rationale comment.\n- [ ] The release-evidence pipeline is **wired** so each job writes its data to a\n  distinctly-named fragment (`evidence-shapin`/`evidence-build`/`evidence-mcp`) and a\n  consolidation job concatenates them into `release-evidence.txt` (job-scoped\n  artifacts cannot be appended across jobs). `test_release_workflow_pins.py` check (f)\n  asserts the *wiring* statically ŌĆö the fragment names **and** the write commands that\n  populate them (e.g. the mcp step redirecting version+digest into `evidence-mcp`), so\n  an empty-file implementation fails the check. The *populated content* of a real run\n  is `[operator-attested]`: the releaser attaches the run's `release-evidence.txt` to\n  the release ticket. (Wheel/sdist SHA-256 sums are added as the `evidence-artifacts`\n  fragment by Finding 3's build-once step, which lands **after** this story, so they\n  are out of scope here.)\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` contains a \"Pinning\" section covering, at minimum: (a) the\n  rationale for full-SHA action pins, (b) the command to regenerate the lock file\n  (`pip-compile --generate-hashes ŌĆ”`), and (c) how to update the MCP publisher pin\n  (version + SHA-256) ŌĆö verified by `test_release_workflow_pins.py` asserting all three\n  exact substrings are present in `docs/releasing.md`: `pip-compile --generate-hashes`,\n  `MCP publisher`, and `full-SHA` (the pinning rationale keyword). Each is a literal\n  `grep -q` so the check is deterministic.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784068115213609001,"uuid":"7c6fe732-8fbd-4f62-a063-2691ae93892c"}